{"title_page": "Winthrop Poll", "text_new": "The Winthrop Poll, also known as the \"Winthrop University Poll,\" is a long-term survey initiative conducted by [[Winthrop University]]'s Center for Public Opinion & Policy Research (CPOPR).<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite book|last=Miller, Blumenthal, Chamberlain (editors)|first=|title=Handbook of Community Sentiment|publisher=Springer|year=2015|isbn=978-1-4939-1899-7|location=|pages=135}}</ref> It informs public policy makers and the general public about the attitudes and opinions of citizens in South Carolina and the southern region of the United States. During the 2020 US Democratic primary, the [[Democratic National Committee]] (DNC) designated the Winthrop Poll as one of the threshold polls used to qualify presidential candidates for debates.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://democrats.org/news/dnc-announces-qualification-criteria-for-nevada-democratic-presidential-primary-debate/|title=DNC Announces Qualification Criteria For Nevada Democratic Presidential Primary Debate|date=2020-01-31|website=Democrats|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/dnc-unveils-qualifiers-democratic-debate-ahead-south-carolina/story?id=69008355|title=DNC unveils qualifications for last Democratic debate ahead of South Carolina primary|last=News|first=A. B. C.|website=ABC News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> Topics of the poll typically include political candidates and politically-relevant issues.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.postandcourier.com/politics/how-the-winthrop-poll-became-scs-barometer-for-tracking-politicians-and-public-opinion/article_8a21e9e6-879d-11e9-aa4b-9b06dac78fa8.html|title=How the Winthrop Poll became SC's barometer for tracking politicians and public opinion|last=cbyrd@postandcourier.com|first=Caitlin Byrd|website=Post and Courier|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Results of the poll are cited regularly by national and international news organizations such as [[Time (magazine)]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/3741415/lindsey-graham-south-carolina-straw-poll/|title=S.C. Presidential Straw Poll Leaves Out Lindsey Graham|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> [[Politico]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2013/05/nikki-haley-south-carolina-governor-91215.html|title=Haley's rocky governorship|last=Schultheis|first=Emily|website=POLITICO|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> [[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]],<ref>{{Cite news|last=Axelrod|first=Tal|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/463897-biden-has-20-point-lead-in-south-carolina-primary-poll|title=Biden has 20-point lead in South Carolina primary: poll|date=|work=The Hill|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> the [[BBC]]<ref name=\":0\" />, [[Washington Post]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/post-partisan/wp/2016/02/17/evangelical-christians-should-not-vote-for-donald-trump/|title=Opinion {{!}} Evangelical Christians should not vote for Donald Trump|first=Ed |last=Rogers |website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>, [[MSNBC]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.msnbc.com/rachel-maddow-show/poll-answers-the-what-happened-lindsey-graham-question|title=Poll answers the 'What happened to Lindsey Graham?' question|date=2019-03-21|website=MSNBC|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>, and [[CNN]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2015/09/30/politics/tim-scott-lindsey-graham-confederate-flag-south-carolina/index.html|title=Poll: Tim Scott more popular than Lindsey Graham in S.C. |first=Elizabeth |last=Landers|website=CNN|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>.  \n\n====== History ======\nProfessor Scott Huffmon began the polling initiative in 2002 as part of a Winthrop University \u201cScope and Methods\u201d research class.<ref name=\":0\" /> The first intrastate polling was conducted in 2003\u00a0and the first statewide poll took place in 2006.\n\nIn 2019, the CPOPR received over three million dollars in grants from the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] and the [[South Carolina Department of Health and Environmental Control|S.C. Department of Health and Environmental Control]] to support support social behavior and health research.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Harris|first=Amanda|url=https://www.heraldonline.com/news/local/education/winthrop-news/article225180855.html|title=How healthy are U.S. citizens? Winthrop to research issue with $3M from SC|date=2019-01-28|work=The Herald|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://palmettoreport.com/2019/02/17/winthrop-awarded-3-4-million-in-state-contracts-for-health-research/|title=Winthrop awarded $3.4 million for health research|date=2019-02-17|website=palmetto report|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n====== Criticism ======\nFew have criticized the poll for being inaccurate<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fitsnews.com/2017/04/12/winthrops-poll-is-becoming-a-joke/|title=Winthrop\u2019s Poll Is Becoming A Joke|last=FITSNews|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> or questionable.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wrhi.com/wrhm/2011/12/huffmon-defends-winthrop-poll-after-attacks-from-scgop/|title=Huffmon defends Winthrop Poll after attacks from SCGOP|date=2011-12-15|website=Interstate 107|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> However, the poll's director, Scott Huffmon, has defended the methodology used. <ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Polling]]\n[[Category:Winthrop University]]\n", "text_old": "{{Notability|date=April 2020}}\nThe Winthrop Poll, also known as the \"Winthrop University Poll,\" is a long-term survey initiative conducted by [[Winthrop University]]'s Center for Public Opinion & Policy Research (CPOPR).<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite book|last=Miller, Blumenthal, Chamberlain (editors)|first=|title=Handbook of Community Sentiment|publisher=Springer|yea